Europe needs migration to reboot.
Brussels – More than 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
At the same time, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking spent the entire summer searching for safe ports where the passengers on their boats could disembark.
The refugee and migrant camps on the island of Lesvos in Greece, as well as other resettlement camps in Libya, are overcrowded.
Turkey tore up the 2016 agreement that halted migrants from entering the EU.
Despite Europe's desire to help migrants and its respect for international law, it does not want its territories to be overpopulated.
In 2015-16, the number of refugees and migrants flooding into the EU surged — many had fled the Syrian war — and this significantly impacted trust within the EU.
The massive influx of immigration is eroding government confidence in the management of the EU's external borders and asylum, and it also highlights the ineffective cooperation with countries of origin.
Thus, immigration has become a political football and a favorite issue for populists.
Under the leadership of President Ursula von der Leyen, the new EU Commission must take control of migration issues again while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this, the EU needs to reassess policies in four key areas and mobilize its member states to take action for the sake of European interests.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping its internal borders open.
Any country that allows free internal movement of its people, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, does not outsource external border control to a single state or region.
Controlling the external borders of the EU must be a collective task, as well as a national one.
The European Border and Coast Guard Agency (Frontex) must be strengthened further and should deploy joint guard teams with member states—including along coastlines and at airports.
The EU also needs to restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal immigration in the Mediterranean.
Secondly, Europe needs to deal with economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Merging them into one has already pushed the asylum system to the brink of collapse, and distinguishing between them would help ensure that migrants who fear for their lives can be heard with their rights protected.
To address the genuine economic and social needs of the EU, an effective blue or green card policy for economic immigration is required, along with the implementation of overall immigration targets.
These mechanisms cannot be introduced only during the next migration crisis; they must be considered now.
To achieve this, the EU must break taboos.
First, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Secondly, policies must clarify which immigrants are welcome.
Third, member states must identify what kind of EU assistance they need to facilitate smooth migration processes.
Finally, visas and work permits must be on the table to facilitate the return of unauthorized immigrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaties, each member state is responsible for managing immigration from outside the EU.
However, if the government agrees on a overall EU migration target, that would be a significant step forward.
Conversely, member states can specify the economic migration countries of origin they want and the specific requirements they have, as well as the EU budget resources needed to host them.
In this way, immigration intake would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For instance, Canada has long had proactive immigration policies, selecting immigrants based on criteria such as country of origin, skill level, and age.
Europe can do this as well.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, it is necessary to abandon the one-size-fits-all requirement for the mandatory allocation of asylum seekers within the EU.
This requirement undermines the氛围within the EU, but it could still be feasible if the border, asylum, and migration systems are sufficiently robust and effective.
Moreover, it cannot be expected that the front-line member states of the EU will be able to solve the problem of illegal migration crossing external borders on their own.
The camps are already overcrowded, with migrants suffering abuse at the hands of authorities or being driven northward.
The responsibility of the first member state that immigrants arrive in must be supplemented by the EU's solidarity.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to help streamline the behavior and management capabilities of national asylum agencies.
Only in this way can decisions of the state be respected throughout the Schengen area and ensure the integrity of the cross-border travel zone.
After streamlining the behavior and management capabilities of national asylum agencies, the processing procedures for asylum applications can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should build stronger win-win cooperation with countries of origin and transit.
To facilitate the deportation of migrants who are legally prohibited from entering the EU back to their countries of origin, such connections are crucial.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic policy tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in areas such as security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's migration goals, as well as skills cooperation to prepare for jobs in Europe, can be offered to third countries that aspire to secure stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of immigration.
This includes the population explosion in Sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and shortages of job opportunities.
The EU’s aid should aim to restore stability and reduce risks by supporting security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area could make investments more secure, unlocking private and domestic finance to drive national economic growth, job creation, and provide an alternative to migration.
The new EU Commission has the opportunity to steer the Union away from its instinctive reactions to migration crises and toward a more consistent and sustained approach, both internally and externally.
We must not miss this opportunity.
